bib_record.title: Correlated n-gamma angular distributions from the Q = 4.4398 MeV 12C(n,n'g) reaction for incident neutron energies from 6.5 MeV to 16.5 MeV

free_txt: Experiment performed at the Weapons
Neutron Research facility at LANSCE, Los Alamos
Detector efficiencies were calculated by Monte
Carlo methods
Corrections for in target multiple scattering
were applied
Neutrons and gamma rays were detected using
array of 54 EJ-309 liquid scintillator detectors each
with an R4144 Hamamatsu PMT readout. Detectors are
placed at nine evenly spaced polar angles from
30 deg to 150 deg with respect to the beam direction,
and at azimuthal angles of +-24 deg, 57 deg  and
90 deg with respect to vertical.
Probably total uncertainty, but their
origin is not described
Experiment performed at the Weapons
Neutron Research facility at LANSCE, Los Alamos
The measurements were carried out at
WNR flight path 15L, located 21.5 m from the spallation
target and 15 deg to the left of the incident pulsed
proton beam axis. Each proton micropulse was a 150-ps
wide, separated by approximately 1.8 mu-s from
neighboring micropulse. Each macropulse consists of
approximately 347 micropulses. WNR received an average
of 100 macropulses per second during this experiment.
A timing signal, was provided to the experimental area
indicating each new proton micropulse. Signals from
detectors were digitized. Neutron and gamma signals
were separated based on the PSD ratio of the pulse
tail integral to the full pulse integral.
Coincidences were assembled offline
Graphite sample of cylindrical shape approximately
1" diameter and 2.5" long.
